<![CDATA[ <figure><img alt="" src="https://cdn-images-1.medium.com/max/1024/1*vkyuNu5dqdVz5X0AxCy5tQ.jpeg" /></figure><p>Being a programmer is not an easy journey even having many resources available, most of them for free. Overconsumption of content and a lack of direction may bring the idea that you are disoriented. And there is a high chance that you truly are!</p><p>This feeling could reach any level in this career. We wrongly believe that only people that are transitioning to Software Engineering face this situation. False! I&#39;ve mentored a lot of Senior Engineers that felt <strong>stuck </strong>too!</p><p>This post aims to bring the right mindset for Software Engineers that I got from 13 years of experience.</p><h3>The growth mindset</h3><p>Learning hurts, there is no other way. If you truly want to learn, be ready to expose yourself to very frustrating situations.</p><p>Imagine that you want to learn how to play guitar. You try the first chords, your fingers are so rusted and you can barely touch the strings with the right strength. After 15 minutes of trying to play that easy song that you love‚Ä¶ you can&#39;t handle the pain. You must stop!</p><p>In Software Engineering the same happens. It takes time to learn new concepts. You will suffer to make your first program alone. You will also suffer to understand Design Systems, SOLID, Clean Code, Design Patterns all these advanced concepts. Rookies or Seniors, we will suffer.</p><p>But the time will pass anyway. Should we get afraid of this? Of course not! We must understand that someday, somehow, we will have a huge spike in our learning curve as this chart shows.</p><figure><img alt="" src="https://cdn-images-1.medium.com/max/1024/1*XN78EIvqWrkBSXo5QQDfiw.jpeg" /><figcaption>Spoiler: This chart repeats over and over again. The maturity phase doesn&#39;t last too long!</figcaption></figure><p>Embrace the pain and enjoy the journey! You are not alone.</p><h3>Practice! Even as a Senior‚Ä¶</h3><p>Technology changes so fast! As Software Engineers we want to serve our Businesses with the best tools ever. But what happens if you get rusty? What happens if there are betters tools in the market that would save time and you have no idea? Well, I witnessed great people succumbing to laziness and comfort.</p><blockquote>I still remember‚Ä¶ They felt so secure, the tech market was an oasis. Everywhere you look there are Tech Recruiters begging for attention. LinkedIn inboxes? Full of offers‚Ä¶ C&#39;mon, we are kings! Then, the layoffs started, people got scared and the lazier team workers were <strong>fired</strong>.</blockquote><p>Getting back from this situation is hard. Who wants a guitar player in your band that is rusty and doesn&#39;t know the new trends? No one!</p><p>Programmers, please listen to me. Watch tutorials and code. Get a bootcamp and then code. Get a coffee, then code. Go to the bathroom, then code. Ask for reviews, then code again. Get an idea, then code. Repeat it without &quot;a break&quot;.</p><p>Chefs that know all recipes but don‚Äôt cook are worthless. Same for Software Engineers that don‚Äôt practice and don‚Äôt know the foundations to build things from scratch.</p><h3>Soft skills are (g)old</h3><p>Invest in soft skills. I know they look outdated! You may think: ‚ÄúWe live in a digital world. In a world of emojis! Why should I learn to be a better communicator?‚Äù</p><p>I‚Äôve interviewed and mentored probably more than one hundred people and trust me, programmers that know how to get their job done with great communication, accountability, respect, and quality are gold. I want them on my team at all costs.</p><h3>Dream &amp; Believe</h3><p>My daughters love to tell stories. They create those stories where they have powers and can fight against wolves and lions. Unfortunately, I feel that we lost this power of <strong>dreaming</strong>. Do you remember that question: ‚ÄúWhat do you want to be when you grow up?‚Äù We were used to dreaming.</p><p>Most engineers, especially seniors, lost their dreams somewhere on the road. I have my theories, but I still don‚Äôt have the courage to try a final answer for this phenomenon.</p><p>Even though, I‚Äôd love to invite you to dream again. Dream high! Write your dreams in a paper, in Google Docs, and share it with your loved ones. Then‚Ä¶ execute it.</p><p>It will take time, but don‚Äôt stop, don‚Äôt quit. One of the biggest differences between successful people and unsuccessful people is that they don‚Äôt stop. Remember the learning curve chart‚Ä¶ it takes time, maybe years, maybe decades.</p><h3>The BIG invite</h3><p>Finally, I want to invite you to my <strong>free mentorship</strong>. It took a long time in my career to get a mentor and it was a big game changer. This mentorship will happen every Monday, 8 pm EST.</p><p>The idea is simple, let&#39;s build a community! Let&#39;s sit down together, share experiences, stories, obstacles, talk about interviews, review code, pair programming, and so much more. Someday you could even be the leader of the meeting, why not? Let&#39;s help each other in this chaotic world.</p><p>Helping each other is like being a conductor. Some people are like lamps that have all the potential within but there is no electricity passing through them. They just need a little help to shine‚Ä¶</p><p>I&#39;ve been there. I also felt stuck, but I can help you. Just send me a message on my LinkedIn and I will share more information.</p><p><a href="https://www.linkedin.com/in/gabriel-avila/">https://www.linkedin.com/in/gabriel-avila/</a></p><p>Don&#39;t miss this opportunity! I don&#39;t know for how long I will keep this mentorship. The time is <strong>now!</strong></p><p>If this is not interesting to you, help some lamps out there. Please share this post and this BIG invite. I count on you! Let&#39;s shineüí°</p><img src="https://medium.com/_/stat?event=post.clientViewed&referrerSource=full_rss&postId=bd492f82fda5" width="1" height="1" alt=""> ]]>
</content:encoded>
