<atom:updated>2021-10-22T11:23:07.686Z</atom:updated>
<content:encoded>
<![CDATA[ <figure><img alt="" src="https://cdn-images-1.medium.com/max/1024/1*ScaOx8Wu9ivDMyILeJVKBQ.jpeg" /></figure><p>I really want to explain Design Patterns in my own words. As Albert Einstein said:</p><blockquote><em>If you cannot explain it simply, you don‚Äôt understand it well enough.‚Ää‚Äî‚ÄäAlbert Einstein</em></blockquote><p>So, let‚Äôs try to explain Design Patterns simply and in my own words with some examples in Typescript, a coding language that I‚Äôm working on more nowadays.</p><p>Let‚Äôs see this Design Pattern called <strong>Singleton</strong>. I know that this Design Pattern could be the simplest one, but still is important to understand its foundations to be able to use it properly.</p><p>When you understand how the tool works, you have the ability to not be limited by just one point of view or just one use case, you can see the whole landscape and maybe use this tool in more cases.</p><h3>Why Design Patterns?</h3><p>Software engineering is a hard field with a lot of problems. Those architectural problems probably were already solved by someone and there is a guide to follow which we call ‚ÄúDesign Patterns‚Äù.</p><p>The point is: don‚Äôt try to recreate a solution that already exists. Be smart! Learn with the previous ‚Äúgenerations‚Äù and create something better, based on previous knowledge, for the next generations. That‚Äôs how Software Engineering will evolve.</p><blockquote><em>Learn from previous solutions, create better systems, leave a bigger legacy for the next Software Engineers.</em></blockquote><p>We should stand on the giant‚Äôs shoulders! Check out my Medium profile to see all other Design Patterns articles that I‚Äôve written.</p><h3>The problem</h3><p>We have an integration app that should sync two systems: Hubspot and Zoho. We are going to sync only the <em>Contacts</em> object from scratch. Both systems should have the same contacts list.</p><p>This app is going to sync both systems every 30 seconds and that‚Äôs a client‚Äôs requirement. On each execution, only the new items will be brought from both systems.</p><p>However, what happens if we have a big payload on execution #1 and it takes 40 seconds to be finished, and then, execution #2 already started 10 seconds ago? Can you see this snowball effect? üòÖ</p><p>Well, in this case, execution #1 and execution #2 will basically see the same state from both systems, which means we might have duplicated creation requests. Also, Hubspot and Zoho do not have unique keys, so we will see duplicated objects if we make the POST request twice.</p><p>That‚Äôs a big problem! We don‚Äôt want to see duplicated objects. How can we solve that?</p><h3>Singleton</h3><p>Singletons ensure that exists only one instance for that class. Singletons have this workflow:</p><ul><li>Do we already have an instance built?</li><li>No: Build it</li><li>Yes: Return the built instance previously</li></ul><p>Why is that important? It‚Äôs important because it ensures we have only one instance for that class and that could help us on:</p><ul><li>Reduce the amount of memory usage</li><li>Create one global point on the entire system, i.e. we have the same state on the entire system</li></ul><p>That‚Äôs why Singleton is most used to dealing with database connections. It‚Äôs preferable to have as few connections as possible and Singleton does that pretty well.</p><p>But that does not mean that Singletons can only be used for Database Connections. We could use them to store params, configurations, definitions, service locators, or items that are useful on different parts of your app.</p><h3>Applying the Singleton Pattern</h3><p>To apply the Singleton Design Pattern we should:</p><ul><li>Create the instance static attribute which will be null or the built object</li><li>Turn the constructor private. With that, no one can create new objects of this class</li><li>Create a static method that will work as the constructor</li></ul><figure><img alt="" src="https://cdn-images-1.medium.com/max/568/1*4yQhvChJMrk-Vg3VpRZx3w.png" /><figcaption>Example of Singleton‚Äôs structure</figcaption></figure><h3>CreateRequestsStore</h3><p>Getting back to our problem, to avoid duplicated requests we can create the <em>CreateRequestsStore, </em>which will be a Singleton to store the hashes of the requests in process<em>.</em></p><p>Basically, the idea here is:</p><ul><li>Integration app runs</li><li>It brings the new items from both systems (Hubspot and Zoho)</li><li>It goes on each new object to be created</li><li>It creates a hash of the object to be created</li><li>It checks if this hash already exists on the <em>CreateRequestsStorage</em> Singleton</li><li>If it does, skip the request to avoid duplicated requests</li><li>If it does not, make the request</li><li>When the request is finished, schedule execution in 2 minutes to remove this hash from <em>CreateRequestsStorage </em>through <em>setTimeout </em>(we really want to ensure that we won‚Äôt have duplicated data, 2 minutes sounds good)</li></ul><p>With that Singleton, we can avoid duplicated requests in run time. The <em>CreateRequestStore</em> class will look like this:</p><figure><img alt="" src="https://cdn-images-1.medium.com/max/588/1*J_1Tytl6TmmZ8oSpn_sTmw.png" /></figure><p>Explaining the public methods, we have:</p><ul><li><em>getOrBuild()</em><strong><em>: </em></strong>to get or build the instance</li><li><em>addRequest()</em>: to add a new request object into the store. It returns the built hash</li><li><em>isRequestInProcess()</em>: to verify if the request object is in process</li><li><em>removeRequestByHash()</em>: to remove the hash from requests in the process list</li></ul><h3>SyncHubspotZoho</h3><p>Now the <em>SyncHubspotZoho</em> just needs to use the <em>CreateRequestsStore </em>and it should work as we agreed above. It will look like this:</p><figure><img alt="" src="https://cdn-images-1.medium.com/max/924/1*fbhcpBW8786muPfdafnMUg.png" /></figure><p>This class is getting all the new contacts from both systems and creating them on each other (Hubspot to Zoho; Zoho to Hubspot) only when the object to be created does not exist on <em>CreateRequestsStore. </em>The hash of the object is removed 2 minutes later its creation.</p><p>Since the sync will happen every 30 seconds and we might have big payloads, in this case, the execution could delay and the next execution would start before the previous one finishes. This snowball effect might generate duplicated creation requests, but this solution will totally avoid this undesired behavior.</p><p>P.S.: This code above is not concerned about retrying policies, errors, or anything else. The focus here is a real usage of Singleton.</p><h3>Use Singleton wisely</h3><p>There are tons of articles saying that Singletons violate the Single Responsibility Principle. Since any part of the system can mutate its state, it could cause bugs. Also, bad programmers could use the Singleton to store anything.</p><p>I don‚Äôt completely agree with them. I believe that using Singleton pretentiously might cause bugs and it will violate SRP.</p><p>Here where I work, we had to create a Singleton to store some definitions to be used in the entire app. It worked great without causing bugs or bringing confusion to our system.</p><p>Although I agree that most lazy developers would use Singleton in a bad way, without thinking about the pros and cons, just using it pretentiously. So, to make your Singleton not violate the SRP:</p><ul><li><strong>Do only one thing in your Singleton</strong>.</li></ul><p>In this example, we just use this Single as a store for hashes. That‚Äôs it!</p><p>With that, you can avoid coupling too many things in your Singleton. Be wise! Design Patterns should be the solution, not the problem.</p><h3>Conclusion</h3><p>Now we can understand a little bit more of this simple and kind of underrated Design Pattern that could be so useful on the right hands.</p><p>After my studies, I believe that Singletons are great when you have to create a unique object:</p><ul><li>Seeking to reduce the amount of memory usage or resources, like Database Connections</li><li>Or it should be available on the entire system like Definitions, Configuration, Service Locators, i.e. simple stores.</li></ul><p>I hope that this article can turn you into a great developer that will use this Design Pattern wisely.</p><img src="https://medium.com/_/stat?event=post.clientViewed&referrerSource=full_rss&postId=c247f00b7350" width="1" height="1" alt=""> ]]>
</content:encoded>
