<![CDATA[ <p>This post will be very short, it‚Äôs more like a reminder to myself. So often I need to store a list of seeds executed as migrations do on Sequelize. It‚Äôs easy to configure CI/CD to run all seeds since our seeds have the domain data.</p><p>However, when I need it for bigger projects, I often forget how to do it. So, here we go:</p><figure><img alt="" src="https://cdn-images-1.medium.com/max/309/1*vf-2mpIcV-xdqJxDOrq-eQ.png" /></figure><p>That‚Äôs it! We just need to set the <strong>seederStorage</strong> attribute and we are fine!</p><figure><img alt="" src="https://cdn-images-1.medium.com/max/320/0*r563JpSDiGU1P9IY.gif" /></figure><p>It‚Äôs important to remember that we have the following options:</p><ul><li>sequelize: Where Sequelize will store the executed seeds on the database (also, you can set a table name, different from the default name ‚ÄúSequelizeData‚Äù)</li><li>json: It will store the executed seeds in a JSON file</li><li>none: It will not save the executed seeds</li></ul><p>I really don‚Äôt know why that‚Äôs not the default behavior, but‚Ä¶ never mind! I already have a post to remember me lol.</p><p>You can read more about it on <a href="https://sequelize.org/master/manual/migrations.html#seed-storage">Sequelize Documentation‚Ää‚Äî‚ÄäSeed Storage Section</a></p><img src="https://medium.com/_/stat?event=post.clientViewed&referrerSource=full_rss&postId=945ce1e18415" width="1" height="1" alt=""> ]]>
